ardin","meanings":["English: variant of   Barden  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Bairdín</b>, see   Barden   4.","French: from a pet form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bardo</i>, from <i>barta</i> ‘battle axe’ (see   Bard   1)."]},{"name":"Bardon","meanings":["English: habitational name from Bardon in Leicestershire, named with Old English <i>berg</i> ‘hill, mound, barrow’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’, meaning ‘barrow hill’.","English: variant of   Barden  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <i>Ó Bárdáin</i>, see   Barden   4."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was